Not a big deal, you can simply wrap your code in a loop! This will make it so the code is repeated over and over again:

loop {
    move(right)
}

You can check for this by calling "laserCanShoot":

if laserCanShoot() {
    print("can shoot!")
} else {
    print("cannot shoot yet")
}

Similar to "playerDir", the "radarRobotDir"-function then tells you the direction towards the last selected robot. This code for example shows the directions to all robots found by the radar:

radarSearch()
while radarNext() {
    print(radarRobotDir())
}

An interesting fact is that "radarNext" selects the found robots in order of increasing distance. This means that to only do something for the closest found robot, you can just use an "if"-statement:

radarSearch()
if radarNext() {
    print(radarRobotDir())
}
